{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17637533","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17637533"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:43:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:43:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17667"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17667","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17667"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10381"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77888"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10381","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10381"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17667"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63373"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4933"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10537"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24269"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24595"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26716"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77888","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77888"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old woman is brought to the Emergency Department after participating in a water drinking competition. She had consumed 6 L of water over the previous three hours. She is confused and has a headache. Her serum sodium is 128 mmol/L (135-145).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWater intoxication occurs when water intake exceeds the excretory capacity of the kidneys, leading to potentially dangerous fluid and electrolyte disturbances.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the maximum rate of water excretion by healthy kidneys?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["200 mL/hr","500 mL/hr","1000 mL/hr","2000 mL/hr","3000 mL/hr"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003E1000 mL/hr\u003C/strong\u003E represents the approximate maximum rate at which healthy kidneys can excrete excess water. This limitation exists even with complete suppression of antidiuretic hormone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E2000 mL/hr\u003C/strong\u003E exceeds the physiological capacity of the kidneys to excrete free water.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E200 mL/hr\u003C/strong\u003E is insufficient for normal renal water handling and would result in fluid retention even with normal intake.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E3000 mL/hr\u003C/strong\u003E is well beyond the maximum physiological capacity of renal water excretion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E500 mL/hr\u003C/strong\u003E would be inadequate to handle typical daily fluid loads and maintain homeostasis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding this limitation is important because water intake exceeding this rate can lead to water intoxication, resulting in hypotonic hyponatraemia. When serum sodium falls rapidly due to excessive water intake, water moves into cells causing them to swell. This is particularly dangerous in the brain, where cellular swelling can lead to cerebral oedema.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Water intoxication causes hypotonic hyponatraemia due to excessive free water intake exceeding the kidney\u0027s excretion capacity.","The maximum rate of water excretion by healthy kidneys is approximately 800-1000 mL per hour.","Symptoms of water intoxication include headache, confusion, seizures, and cerebral oedema due to cellular swelling."],"references":["Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Philadelphia, PA: Elsevier; 2020.","Tortora, G. J., Mellifont, R., Derrickson, B., Burkett, B., Peoples, G., D, D. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, Asia-Pacific Edition,  2nd Edition. John Wiley \u0026 Sons Australia; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63373"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17667"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63373","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63373"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-08T20:22:23+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-08T20:22:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10381"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77888"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"t